"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782106","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-08","<p>Plans for the move of No. 4 School of Technical Training from St Athan continue to evolve and it is not possible to say when they will be ready for publication.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-11-08T16:10:02.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782106/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782106/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-01","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2017 to Question 107893, when he plans to publish plans for the transfer of No. 4 School of Technical Teaching from St Athan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","110836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782107","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>We know how important it is that children with medical conditions are supported to enjoy a full education. That is why we introduced the duty, under section 100 of the Children and Families Act 2014, to require governing bodies to make arrangements to support pupils with medical conditions and have provided statutory guidance outlining schools’ responsibilities in this area.</p><p> </p><p>We keep this statutory guidance under review. We will continue to ensure that it clearly sets out the arrangements that governing boards should be making to support pupils with medical conditions, based on best practice.</p><p> </p><p>All governing boards should ensure that the school's policy for supporting pupils with medical conditions is reviewed regularly and is readily accessible to parents and school staff.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-09T14:56:25.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782107/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782107/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Pupils: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will amend the statutory guidance entitled Supporting pupils with medical conditions at school to include a requirement for all schools to publish their medical conditions policies.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","110875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782108","Department for Education","false","2017-11-06","<p>The department has no childcare facilities on its estate. There are two schemes in place, salary sacrifice and salary plus, which assist staff with childcare costs.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-06T16:41:52.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782108/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782108/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Department for Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what childcare facilities her Department makes available for staff; how much her Department spent (a) overall and (b) per child on those childcare facilities in the last year; and how many staff members use those childcare facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","110797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782109","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>The attached tables provides information as requested on the number of pupils receiving permanent and fixed period exclusions by special educational needs provision in schools in Gloucestershire local authority and the number and rate of exclusions for pupils with autism as their primary need in Gloucestershire local authority and England.</p><p>Exclusions of pupils with Learning Difficulties Assessments and for schools outside of England are not collected by the department.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","110785 ; 110786","2017-11-09T15:06:29.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782109/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782109/answer","110785 Attach.xlsx","110785, 110786, 110787","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782109/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Autism: Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average rate of exclusion for children with autism as their primary need was in (a) Gloucestershire and (b) the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","110787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782110","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>The attached tables provides information as requested on the number of pupils receiving permanent and fixed period exclusions by special educational needs provision in schools in Gloucestershire local authority and the number and rate of exclusions for pupils with autism as their primary need in Gloucestershire local authority and England.</p><p>Exclusions of pupils with Learning Difficulties Assessments and for schools outside of England are not collected by the department.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","110786 ; 110787","2017-11-09T15:06:29.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782110/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782110/answer","110785 Attach.xlsx","110785, 110786, 110787","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782110/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Special Educational Needs: Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children with an (a) Education, Health and Care plan, (b) Statement of SEN or (c) Learning Difficulties Assessment received a permanent or fixed exclusion within Gloucestershire in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","110785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782111","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>The attached tables provides information as requested on the number of pupils receiving permanent and fixed period exclusions by special educational needs provision in schools in Gloucestershire local authority and the number and rate of exclusions for pupils with autism as their primary need in Gloucestershire local authority and England.</p><p>Exclusions of pupils with Learning Difficulties Assessments and for schools outside of England are not collected by the department.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","110785 ; 110787","2017-11-09T15:06:29.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782111/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782111/answer","110785 Attach.xlsx","110785, 110786, 110787","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782111/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Autism: Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in Gloucestershire with autism as their primary need received a permanent or fixed period exclusion in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","110786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782112","Department for Education","false","2017-11-06","<p>The attached table provides the average pupil to teacher ratio[1] in state funded primary schools as reported by schools in Coventry South parliamentary constituency and England in November each year from 2011 to 2016.</p><p> </p><p>[1] The Pupil Teacher Ratios are calculated by dividing the total FTE number of pupils on roll in schools in each year by the total number of FTE teachers in schools in each year. Where schools are not open on Census day (January) they are excluded. See School Workforce Census methodology document for further information: Methodology: SFR25/2017</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-11-06T14:42:12.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782112/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782112/answer","110781 attachment.xlsx","Tables","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782112/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Primary Education: Coventry South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the pupil-teacher ratio was in primary schools in Coventry South constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","110781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782113","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>We understand the term arm’s-length body (ALB) to include non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies and non-ministerial departments. We understand IT assets to mean physical assets such as laptops and mobile phones and digital assets to mean non-physical, digitally held information assets owned by the ALBs.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education (DfE) holds a central list of the IT assets of our executive agencies – Education and Skills Funding Agency, National College for Teaching and Leadership, Standards and Testing Agency – and some of our other ALBs – Institute for Apprenticeships, Office of the Children’s Commissioner, Government Equalities Office, Office of the Schools Adjudicator and the Social Mobility Commission. This list only contains assets supplied to the ALB by the DfE; there may be additional assets held by the ALB that the DfE does not hold information on.</p><p> </p><p>The DfE does not hold a central list of the IT assets of any other ALBs. This is because the DfE does not supply assets to these bodies and does not manage assets on their behalf.</p><p>The DfE’s Information Asset Register, which includes information on digital assets, includes assets of our executive agencies only.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-09T14:53:36.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782113/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782113/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Department for Education: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782114","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>The department is committed to ensuring all parents who are eligible for the 30 hours free childcare entitlement are able to take up a place that suits their childcare needs. That is why we ran a £100 million early years capital bid round, for which local authorities, in partnership with providers, were invited to submit bids. Over 350 projects across 123 local authorities were successful in this bid round – six of which were located in Hampshire.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities have a duty to secure childcare provision free of charge to qualifying children. They are, therefore, best placed to ensure parents in their area have a sufficient choice of childcare. As of 31 August, over 216,000 codes were issued for the autumn term, with 90% being validated as of 9 October.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-09T15:02:21.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782114/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782114/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress her Department is making on the provision of and parental choice on 30 hours of childcare to working parents in Hampshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","110716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782115","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-08","<p>My Department’s arm’s-length bodies are responsible for maintaining records of their own IT and Digital assets, except for those assets managed as part of the Defra group contract with IBM.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-08T12:06:19.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782115/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782115/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782116","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Secretary of State has had productive discussions with the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy as we design a future agricultural policy to best support our farmers to grow more, sell more and export more great British food. I have also met with BEIS ministers to discuss these issues.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-08T17:13:33.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782116/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782116/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on Government support for the food and farming sectors after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782117","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Committee on Climate Change (CCC) have identified a number of improvements to the greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions inventory. They particularly encouraged the inclusion of new guidelines on wetlands (which cover peatlands) from the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change<sup>1 </sup>to fully assess their impacts. Further research is required before these guidelines can be fully applied in our national GHG inventory. This is currently underway and will feed into the inventory over the next few years.</p><p> </p><p><sup>[1]</sup> IPCC 2014, 2013 Supplement to the 2006 IPCC Guidelines for National Greenhouse Gas Inventories: <a href="http://www.ipcc-nggip.iges.or.jp/public/wetlands/" target="_blank">http://www.ipcc-nggip.iges.or.jp/public/wetlands/</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-11-08T12:56:14.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782117/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782117/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Peat: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress the Government is making on implementing the recommendations of the Committee on Climate Change report Meeting Carbon Budgets - 2016 Progress Report to Parliament, published in June 2016, on including peatland within the UK's carbon inventory by 2018.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","110754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782118","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Forestry Commission estimates that there are 15,000 red squirrels in England and over two million grey squirrels. This estimate dates from 2014 and no more recent data are available. The red squirrel population is fragmented, occurring only in isolated populations on the islands in Poole Harbour, on the Isle of Wight and across the north of England.</p><p> </p><p>Wildlife management is a devolved matter and so the conservation of species in other parts of the UK is a matter for the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-06T11:59:56.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782118/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782118/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Squirrels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) red and (b) grey squirrels in each region of the UK in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","110767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782119","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-13","<p>Defra does not provide in house childcare facilities for employees.</p><p> </p><p>However, Defra recognises that employees need flexible pre-school and out-of-school childcare that is convenient to them and therefore provides access to a salary sacrifice scheme for childcare vouchers. The Scheme enables employees to choose their own childcare provider and to have their childcare costs reduced by using Childcare Vouchers. The vouchers can be used to pay any eligible childcare provider that is OFSTED registered and HMRC compliant.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-13T11:01:03.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782119/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782119/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what childcare facilities his Department makes available for staff; how much his Department spent (a) overall and (b) per child on those childcare facilities in the last year; and how many staff members use those childcare facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","110801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782120","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-08","<p>We hope to publish draft legislation for consultation around the turn of the year, as announced on 30 September.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-08T17:03:34.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782120/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782120/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to introduce legislation to increase the maximum sentence for animal cruelty offences to five years' imprisonment.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","110791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782121","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-08","<p>The dairy industry is a very important contributor to the economy of South West England, with the region home to over 38% of England’s breeding dairy cows (and 23.75% of the UK’s) and 37% of England’s dairy holdings and producers. Government has made no specific assessment of the growth in the dairy industry in the South West in recent years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Nevertheless, a report published by the National Farmers Union in October 2016 <a href="https://www.nfuonline.com/assets/67942" target="_blank">https://www.nfuonline.com/assets/67942</a> gives an insight on growing trends of the dairy industry in the South West.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-08T17:40:41.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782121/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782121/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Dairy Farming: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the growth in the dairy industry in the South West.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","110832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782122","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>Defra does not fund research into the development of individual insecticides; this would fall to the agrochemical sector. A number of public bodies fund broader research into pest control chemicals, biological controls and cultural methods. This includes funding from Innovate UK through mechanisms including the Agri-Tech Catalyst, which helps develop innovative solutions to challenges in crop production. Any Defra research into alternatives to current chemical pesticides can be found at: <a href="http://randd.defra.gov.uk" target="_blank">http://randd.defra.gov.uk</a>.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-07T17:43:29.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782122/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782122/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Insecticides: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what research his Department has funded to investigate alternatives to neonicotinoid insecticides; and if he will provide a list of that research.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","110805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782123","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>Marine and fisheries management issues are devolved matters for UK Overseas Territories (UKOT), who are responsible for managing fishing licensing issues, including vessel allocations. In terms of international quota allocations, however, St Helena (including Ascension and Tristan da Cunha), Bermuda, BVI and Turks and Caicos are part of the UKOT membership to the International Convention for the Conservation of Atlantic Tunas (ICCAT). Within ICCAT, the UKOTs have been allocated quota for bigeye tuna (2,100t), albacore (100t), swordfish (25t), which is divided between these territories, based on historical interests.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-07T17:53:59.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782123/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782123/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Fishing Catches: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what fishing tonnage quota is assigned to the UK for each of its Overseas Territories; and what fishing quota is assigned to each vessel.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782124","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>Sudan is a Human Rights Priority Country for the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office, and we remain concerned about the human rights situation in Sudan. We used the fourth round of the UK-Sudan Strategic Dialogue to agree steps that the Government of Sudan would take to further progress on human rights issues, and to raise again our concerns.</p><p>We welcomed the recent release and pardoning of six human rights activists, including Dr Mudawi Ibrahim Adam, an issue on which we actively lobbied the Government of Sudan. However, a number of human rights challenges remain. The UK will continue to be a strong advocate of the work that human rights defenders do in Sudan. Our Embassy in Khartoum maintains a regular dialogue with the Government of Sudan on human rights issues, and we will continue to lobby them on individual cases of particular concern.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-13T14:31:32.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782124/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782124/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Sudan: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support the UK is giving to human rights defenders working in Sudan.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","110959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782125","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>​The UK is committed to strengthening the links between the Commonwealth. The only category of Commonwealth membership is that of sovereign states. The UK will discuss the policy priorities for the Heads of Government Meeting with the Overseas Territories ahead of next April and represent them at the summit.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T18:03:11.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782125/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782125/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782125/answer/previousversion/20506","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","British Overseas Territories: Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether observer status will be provided for British Overseas Territories during the Commonwealth Summit in London in April 2018.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","110905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782126","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>While we have not raised this specific issue, we have consistently called on the Israeli Government to ease movement and access restrictions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories. We are supporting the UN Access Coordination Unit who work with the Israeli Government, Palestinian Authority (PA) and aid agencies to facilitate the transfer of humanitarian goods including medical equipment and supplies. We are aware that Israeli hospitals do treat Palestinian patients following referrals from the PA.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T17:55:58.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782126/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782126/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782126/answer/previousversion/20501","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Israeli counterpart on medical exit permits for patients needing to leave Gaza, including cancer patients.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","110863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782127","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>We are monitoring the situation in Northern Iraq closely, including in Kirkuk. We are working with the United States, the UN and our Coalition partners to urge all parties to continue to take steps to de-escalate the situation, coordinate security arrangements and avoid violence.</p><p>I discussed the situation with the Iraqi Foreign and Interior Ministers on 17 October. The Foreign Secretary spoke to Prime Minister Abadi on 19 and 29 October, and to Kurdish Prime Minister Nechirvan Barzani on 29 October. On all of these occasions we made it clear that we support Iraq's unity and territorial integrity, and that the long-term security and prosperity of all Iraqis can only be met through dialogue and cooperation. The Foreign Secretary also underlined to Prime Minister Barzani the importance of Kurdish parties resolving their differences.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T18:00:57.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782127/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782127/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782127/answer/previousversion/20505","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Iraq: Kurds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the Government of Iraq on movement of Iraqi Government troops and pro-Iraqi Government militias into Kirkuk; and what steps he has taken to promote dialogue on a democratic future in Kurdistan.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","110867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782128","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Our Embassy in Damascus closed in 2012 and as such the Foreign Secretary is unable to make any representations on Mr Letts' case. While Mr Letts remains in Syria, we are unable to offer any consular assistance. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office advise against all travel to Syria.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T17:57:24.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782128/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782128/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782128/answer/previousversion/20498","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Jack Letts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made and to whom on Jack Letts, who is currently detained in prison in Syria.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","110858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782129","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Home Office does not hold the data requested.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-07T16:09:42.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782129/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782129/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","EU Nationals: Immigration Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many bail applications were made by EU nationals held in immigration detention over the last 12 months; and how many of those applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","110859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782130","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>While we have not raised this issue specifically, we are clear that medical staff should have the protection that allows them to do their jobs in safety.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T18:02:39.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782130/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782130/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782130/answer/previousversion/20499","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","West Bank: Hospitals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Israeli counterparts on accountability for attacks on medical teams by Israeli forces, including the recent raid of al Makassed hospital in East Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","110862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782131","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Foreign Office does not hold data centrally on secondees' individual pension arrangements, nor on who is in receipt of an EU pension.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-11-06T17:38:33.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782131/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782131/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","EU Institutions: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK civil servants who have been seconded to the EU are in receipt of a pension; and what the average pension income is per year.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","110852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782132","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>There are currently 66 UK civil servants known to the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office who are seconded to the EU. Civil servants who are formally seconded to the EU remain on their department's payroll and terms and conditions of service, and accrue pension rights according to membership of one of the six Civil Service pension schemes. The FCO does not hold the data centrally on secondees' individual pension arrangements.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-11-06T13:37:06.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782132/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782132/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","EU Institutions: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK civil servants who have been seconded to the EU are accruing pension rights.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","110853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782133","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office (FCO) has on-site nursery facilities in King Charles Street, London, and Hanslope Park, Milton Keynes. King Charles Street can accommodate up to 44 children and Hanslope Park up to 55. 84 staff members currently use these facilities.</p><p>At both facilities, parents pay the majority of the costs but there is also a Departmental contribution for the provision of facilities. In Financial Year 2016/17 costs to the Department were:</p><p />King Charles St - £97,836, with average cost per child of £2,082<p /><p>Hanslope Park - £45,690, with average cost per child of £831.</p><p>The FCO offers childcare vouchers to staff as part of a salary sacrifice arrangement. These vouchers can be used to pay for care at any Ofsted registered nursery or childminder. There is no net cost to the FCO in offering childcare vouchers.</p><p>The FCO also supports staff by making a contribution towards the cost of places at the Westminster Holiday Playscheme. The cost of this in 2016-17 was £9,688. We do not hold data on the number of children/parents who use this facility.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-11-06T15:22:22.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782133/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782133/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what childcare facilities his Department makes available for staff; how much his Department spent (a) overall and (b) per child on those childcare facilities in the last year; and how many staff members use those childcare facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","110800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782134","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Officials from our Embassy in Cairo last discussed the Rafah Crossing with the Egyptian government in October 2017. We continue to urge Egypt to show maximum flexibility in opening the Rafah crossing.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T17:59:25.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782134/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782134/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782134/answer/previousversion/20496","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Gaza: Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Egyptian counterpart on opening the Rafah crossing to the Gaza Strip.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","110794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782135","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>While we have not raised this specific issue, we have consistently called on the Israeli Government to ease movement and access restrictions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories. We are supporting the UN Access Coordination Unit who work with the Israeli Government, Palestinian Authority and aid agencies to facilitate the transfer of humanitarian goods including medical equipment and supplies.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-08T15:20:38.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782135/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782135/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of Israel's border restrictions and permit system on urgent medical care for patients in the West Bank and Gaza.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","110756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782136","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office only holds details of its own IT and digital assets, including those located at arms-length bodies. Separate systems owned and used by the FCO’s arms-length bodies are managed by their own IT departments.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-11-10T09:31:17.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782136/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782136/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782137","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department does not hold a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm’s length bodies.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-11-08T17:37:01.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782137/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782137/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Department of Health: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782138","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The government keeps all taxes under review at fiscal events and we will consider this issue carefully as part of the Autumn Budget process.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-11-06T15:41:23.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782138/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782138/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Food: Consumption","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government has made an assessment of the potential merits of introducing further fiscal measures to reduce the consumption of foods high in sugar and fat.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","110757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782139","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>The information is not collected in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital collects data on respiratory conditions qualified as being either bronchial asthma or non-asthma related. There are no other groupings available. We are therefore unable to break accident and emergency (A&amp;E) attendances down to asthma or lower respiratory tract infections.</p><p> </p><p>A count of unplanned accident and emergency attendances resulting in an admission and a primary diagnosis of respiratory condition, for the financial years between 2010-11 and 2016-17 is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>This is a count of hospital attendances resulting in admissions, not individual patients as the same person may have been admitted into a National Health Service hospital on more than one occasion.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>210,647</p></td><td><p>219,297</p></td><td><p>254,163</p></td><td><p>245,610</p></td><td><p>252,417</p></td><td><p>278,636</p></td><td><p>287,789</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","110774","2017-11-06T15:23:07.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782139/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782139/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Respiratory System: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients were admitted to hospital via accident and emergency departments with a primary diagnosis of lower respiratory tract infection in each of the (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14, (e) 2014-15, (f) 2015-16 and (g) 2016-17 financial years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","110777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782140","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>The information is not collected in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital collects data on respiratory conditions qualified as being either bronchial asthma or non-asthma related. There are no other groupings available. We are therefore unable to break accident and emergency (A&amp;E) attendances down to asthma or lower respiratory tract infections.</p><p> </p><p>A count of unplanned accident and emergency attendances resulting in an admission and a primary diagnosis of respiratory condition, for the financial years between 2010-11 and 2016-17 is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>This is a count of hospital attendances resulting in admissions, not individual patients as the same person may have been admitted into a National Health Service hospital on more than one occasion.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>210,647</p></td><td><p>219,297</p></td><td><p>254,163</p></td><td><p>245,610</p></td><td><p>252,417</p></td><td><p>278,636</p></td><td><p>287,789</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","110777","2017-11-06T15:23:07.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782140/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782140/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Asthma: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients were admitted to hospital via accident and emergency departments with a primary diagnosis of asthma in each of the (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14, (e) 2014-15, (f) 2015-16 and (g) 2016-17 financial years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","110774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782141","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department values highly the enormous contribution made by all staff working across the health and care sectors, including those from other European countries and elsewhere in the world.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to monitor closely the overall staffing levels across the National Health Service and social care. We are also working across Government to ensure there will continue to be a sufficient number of staff to deliver the high quality services on which patients rely following the United Kingdom’s exit from the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister has been very clear that EU citizens living lawfully in the UK at the point when the UK leaves the EU will be allowed to stay.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-11-08T10:58:04.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782141/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782141/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that non-UK NHS staff do not leave the NHS when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","110759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782142","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>Official statistics on abortions in 2017 are not due for publication until June 2018, when they will be released in the ‘Report on abortion statistics in England and Wales for 2017’. 723 women from Northern Ireland accessed abortions in England in 2016.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-11-07T15:25:06.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782142/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782142/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of women from Northern Ireland who have received abortion treatment in England since 29 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782143","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>Patients who are not eligible on medical grounds for patient transport services, but have a low income and receive a qualifying benefit or allowance, can claim a refund for the cost of travelling to hospitals under the 'Healthcare Travel Costs Scheme' (HTCS).</p><p> </p><p>To qualify for help with travel costs under the HTCS, patients must meet three conditions:</p><p> </p><p>- At the time of appointment, the patient or their partner (including civil partners) must be receiving one of the qualifying benefits or allowances, or meet the eligibility criteria of the NHS Low Income Scheme;</p><p>- The patient journey must be made to receive National Health Service-funded non-primary medical or non-primary dental care services, to which the patient has been referred to by a general practitioner (GP), dentist or hospital consultant; and</p><p>- For referrals made by a primary practitioner such a GP or dentist, the service must be provided on a different day and in premises other than those occupied by the practitioner who made the referral.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-08T17:19:54.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782143/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782143/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Patients: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to help elderly patients who are unable to use hospital or community-supplied transport to attend hospital appointments.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782144","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>The provision of specialist physiotherapy for muscle-wasting conditions, or neuromuscular disorders, is a local matter. NHS England has published service specifications for neurological care for both children and adults. These include exemplar service specifications for neuromuscular conditions, inclusive of muscle-wasting conditions, and set out what providers must have in place to offer evidence-based, safe and effective services. This includes access to physiotherapy. This guidance can be found by following the links below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e09-paedi-neurology.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e09-paedi-neurology.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/d04-neurosci-spec-neuro.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/d04-neurosci-spec-neuro.pdf</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Oxford University Hospitals NHS Trust is currently reviewing proposals for physiotherapy service development for patients with muscle-wasting disorders.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-08T17:14:22.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782144/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782144/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Oxford University Hospitals NHS Trust: Physiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to increase specialist physiotherapy provision for children and adults with muscle-wasting conditions at Oxford University Hospitals NHS Trust.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782145","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-08T17:17:56.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782145/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782145/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the number of NHS appointments that are missed due to patients not being able to access transport.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782146","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Secretary of State for Health’s conversations with the Secretary of State for Transport cover a wide range of issues.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-07T15:16:55.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782146/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782146/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Transport on the effect of decreases to (a) bus routes and (b) the frequency of bus services on the ability of older people to access NHS appointments.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782147","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>The United Kingdom has a residence based healthcare system, so overseas visitors are chargeable for National Health Service care unless an exemption category applies in the NHS (Charges to Overseas Visitors) Regulations 2015. Longstanding guidance to the NHS has advised that overseas visitors should pay in advance of accessing NHS care where their needs are non-urgent, meaning that care can safely wait until they return to their country of residence. From 23 October 2017 this has become a legal requirement, set out in the Regulations.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to committing to this change in law, the Government carefully considered the impact it may have. The requirement to pay upfront before accessing non-urgent care does not affect a chargeable overseas visitor’s access to services, except insofar as they are required to pay in advance of receiving non-urgent care. Urgent or immediately necessary care is provided regardless of whether upfront payment has been received. Only clinicians can assess the level of urgency. Consequently there is not expected to be an effect on patient waiting times.</p><p> </p><p>The estimated effects on staff administration costs of the introduced amendment regulations to extend and improve the recovery of costs of overseas visitors and migrants using the NHS who are not eligible for free care are estimated to be £1.7 million in 17/18 and £3.9 million for each subsequent year. This is on top of costs currently incurred in charging non-eligible patients.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-11-08T11:01:14.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782147/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782147/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","NHS: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on (a) patient waiting times and (b) staff administration of the changes introduced by the National Health Service (Changes to Overseas Visitors) (Amendment) Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782148","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-11-07T15:26:05.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782148/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782148/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average time taken to transfer patients from hospitals to social care settings is (a) nationally and (b) in Leigh constituency.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782149","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>National Health Service trusts and foundation trusts in England all already have a statutory responsibility to make and recover charges from patients who are not ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom and are chargeable for their healthcare.</p><p> </p><p>Upfront charging of overseas visitors for non-urgent or immediately necessary care has been recommended best practice by the Department for several years, including in published national charging guidance.</p><p> </p><p>The published impact assessment estimates a £9 million income for 2017/18 and £23 million for each subsequent year from mandating upfront charging. It is also estimated than an extra income of £9 million for 2017/18 and £21 million for each subsequent year would be identified due to increased compliance since amendments to the charging regulations were made. We expect these incomes to be identified on top of<em> </em>the currently identified income from visitors and migrants, which in 2016/17 amounted to £81 million.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not have estimates for each of the last five years on the number of upfront charges collected for non-ordinarily residents.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-11-08T18:48:32.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782149/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782149/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","NHS: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the amount of non-ordinarily resident upfront charges collected in each of the last five years; and what amount is expected to be collected in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","110819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782150","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>Since the financial year 2014/15, the amounts written off as bad debt in relation to direct charges made to overseas visitors and migrants are part of National Health Service trusts’ and foundation trusts’ annual accounts and are published on Gov.uk broken down by NHS trust.</p><p> </p><p>According to the published annual accounts, there have been £17 million in 2014/15, £16 million in 2015/16, and £17 million in 2016/17 written off as bad debt in relation to direct charges made to overseas visitors and migrants across England. At the same time, direct charges made to overseas visitors and migrants have increased from £47 million in 2014/15, through £69 million in 2015/16, to £81 million in 2016/17.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-11-08T11:02:51.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782150/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782150/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","NHS: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the level of unpaid NHS charges in each year since 2010, broken down by NHS Trust.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","110820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782151","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-06T15:07:07.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782151/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782151/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Smoking: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which organisations have been contracted by the World Health Organization in support of its international smoking programme funded by his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","110840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782152","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>As recommended in Better Births, local maternity systems have formed across England and are co-producing proposals with local women to make maternity services safer and more personal. Initial proposals have been shared with NHS England regional teams. These proposals are locally owned, and where they have not yet been published, the proposals will be published in due course, as part of continuing local engagement and co-production with women, staff and other stakeholders.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-11-08T10:59:44.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782152/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782152/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Maternity Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many local maternity systems plans have been submitted to NHS England; and when he plans to make those plans publicly available.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","110888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782153","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>One United Kingdom official has been seconded from the Department to the World Health Organization Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC) Secretariat to lead work on the FCTC 2030 project funded by the Department. That official’s job title is Team Leader - Development Assistance and the staffing costs are funded by the Department.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-06T15:05:47.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782153/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782153/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Smoking: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many officials from the UK are currently (a) employed, (b) contracted or (c) seconded by the World Health Organization on its international smoking programme funded by his Department; what the (i) job titles and (ii) roles are being undertaken including in respect to which country; and whether the costs or salaries of those officials are being reimbursed.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","110841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782154","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>The attached document contains tables provided by the Department to show all funding awarded or proposed, on a competitive basis, utilising section 64 of the Health and Public Services Act 1968.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-11-06T15:17:57.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782154/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782154/answer","PQ110842 Attachment.docx","PQ110842 attached doc.","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782154/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Action On Smoking and Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 4 September 2017 to Question 6854 on Action on Smoking and Health, if he will list those contracts his Department has issued to date that have been competitively tendered and that will utilise section 64 funding and those contracts his Department plans to issue over the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","110842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782155","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>In February 2016, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published a refreshed clinical guideline 72: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder: diagnosis and management. This sets out the evidence-based approach to supporting children over three, young people and adults with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD).</p><p> </p><p>NICE is developing a new guideline on ADHD which is expected to be published in February 2018.</p><p> </p><p>England continues to develop pathways for mental health services, which benefit people with ADHD needing mental health support, to promote evidence-based approaches to care and tackle unwarranted variation in provision. NICE and the National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health have been commissioned to develop these pathways.</p><p> </p><p>Information on waiting times for ADHD diagnosis, or on the waiting time from referral to treatment, is not collected centrally by the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>Information on funding specifically allocated to ADHD treatment by local commissioners in the last seven years is not held centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","110871 ; 110873","2017-11-07T15:23:17.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782155/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782155/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Hyperactivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the waiting time for ADHD diagnosis and treatment.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782156","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>In February 2016, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published a refreshed clinical guideline 72: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder: diagnosis and management. This sets out the evidence-based approach to supporting children over three, young people and adults with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD).</p><p> </p><p>NICE is developing a new guideline on ADHD which is expected to be published in February 2018.</p><p> </p><p>England continues to develop pathways for mental health services, which benefit people with ADHD needing mental health support, to promote evidence-based approaches to care and tackle unwarranted variation in provision. NICE and the National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health have been commissioned to develop these pathways.</p><p> </p><p>Information on waiting times for ADHD diagnosis, or on the waiting time from referral to treatment, is not collected centrally by the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>Information on funding specifically allocated to ADHD treatment by local commissioners in the last seven years is not held centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","110870 ; 110871","2017-11-07T15:23:17.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782156/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782156/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Hyperactivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the waiting time was for ADHD diagnosis and treatment in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782157","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The General Medical Council advises, in their publication ‘Good Medical Practice’ that doctors must explain to patients if they have a conscientious objection to a particular procedure. Doctors must tell patients about their right to see another doctor and make sure they have enough information to exercise that right to arrange to see another doctor who does not hold the same objection.</p><p>The guidance also advises that, if it is not practical for a patient to arrange to see another doctor, arrangements should be made – without delay – for another suitably qualified colleague to advise, treat or refer the patient. Doctors must bear in mind the patient’s vulnerability and act promptly to make sure they are not denied appropriate treatment or services.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","110878","2017-11-08T17:12:55.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782157/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782157/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Contraceptives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of GPs who refuse to prescribe the contraceptive pill due to a conscientious objection.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","110874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782158","Department of Health","true","2017-11-06","<p>In the past 10 years, the Department has paid Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) a total of £16,016.40 in non-grant funding for help in implementing additional strategies targeted at tackling health inequalities.</p><p> </p><p>Grant funding has also been given to ASH as <ins class="ministerial">in the attached table </ins><del class="ministerial">follows</del>. <ins class="ministerial">Any payment to ASH in respect of activity for 2017-18 will depend upon the outcome of a competitive process to secure support for delivery of the Tobacco Control Plan. </ins>The Department’s financial records do not provide the level of detail to confirm whether funding was made under the legal power Section 64 of the Health and Public Services Act 1968 for all of this period. However, local records can confirm <ins class="ministerial">only</ins> Section 64 has been used since the financial year 2012/13.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-06T17:30:52.563Z","2017-11-08T10:47:05.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782158/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782158/answer","Grant Funding to Action on Smoking and Health.docx","Grant Funding to ASH","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782158/answer","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782158/answer/previousversion/20537","Biography information for Steve Brine","17","Health","Health","2017-11-01","Action On Smoking and Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 4 September 2017 to Question 6854, whether his Department has provided funding from non-section 64 sources to the organisation Action on Smoking and Health in the 2017-18 financial year or any of the last 10 financial years.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","110843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782159","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The only category of Commonwealth membership is that of full membership, which is only open to sovereign states. Any decision to create a new membership status would need to be agreed by consensus of Commonwealth Heads of Government. In 2007 the Heads of Government endorsed the recommendation of the Commonwealth committee on membership not to establish any other membership status.</p><p>The UK welcomes applications to join the Commonwealth where countries can demonstrate the necessary requirements and dedication to the Commonwealth's core values, particularly in relation to human rights, good governance and the rule of law. Countries wishing to join the Commonwealth should express their interest to the Commonwealth Secretariat. Decisions on membership are made by consensus of all Commonwealth member states.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T18:03:45.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782159/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782159/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782159/answer/previousversion/20507","Biography information for Alistair Burt","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-01","Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether observer status will be provided for countries which have expressed an interest in joining the Commonwealth during the Commonwealth Summit in London in April 2018.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","110906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782160","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government has recently set out proposals for an ambitious agreement to support our future cooperation with the EU on security and law enforcement.</p><p>Agreeing effective arrangements for surrendering individuals who seek to evade justice by fleeing across country borders will form an important element of our future partnership with the EU.</p><p>The Government’s proposals are set out in full in “<em>Security, Law Enforcement and Criminal Justice – a future partnership paper</em>” which was published on 18 September available on the gov.uk website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/security-law-enforcement-and-criminal-justice-a-future-partnership-paper" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/security-law-enforcement-and-criminal-justice-a-future-partnership-paper</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-07T16:08:24.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782160/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782160/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","European Arrest Warrants: Gibraltar and Spain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's policy is on continued participation in the European Arrest Warrant in order to prevent people using the border between Gibraltar and Spain to evade justice.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","110907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782161","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Data on officers who have left the force are published as part of the police workforce statistics, which can be accessed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>The College of Policing supports chief constables by advising forces on matters of health, safety and welfare and by supporting them in a range of measures to help reduce sickness and stress.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-06T17:24:54.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782161/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782161/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Police: Stress","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what number of police officers left the police force due to workforce stress in each the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782162","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>Information on detention can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638608/detention-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638608/detention-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-09T17:00:32.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782162/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782162/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Detainees: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the longest period is during which an EU national has been held in immigration detention in the UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","110860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782163","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>Those granted refugee status by the Home Office and in receipt of certain work related benefits have access to fully funded English for Speakers of Other Languages courses. For those receiving other benefits and unemployed full funding for the course is available at the provider’s discretion, and for those not receiving benefits the government may provide 50% of the costs.</p><p>Home Office policy is not to provide asylum seekers with publicly funded English for Speakers of Other Languages courses, although they may access courses on a fee paying basis, and providers may waive fees. Asylum claimants awaiting a decision for over six months may receive a 50% contribution to the costs.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-09T15:17:06.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782163/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782163/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Refugees: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to provide asylum seekers and refugees with low levels of English a minimum of six months free English for Speakers of Other Languages provision from the time when they apply for asylum.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782164","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Home Office officials and legal advisers are currently finalising the department’s post-legislative scrutiny assessment of the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011, which will set out how the Act has worked in practice since it came into force, including views from key partners.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-06T17:28:21.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782164/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782164/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what post-legislative scrutiny her Department has carried out on the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782165","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The role of Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) is to be the voice of the people and hold the chief constable to account, making the police answerable to the communities they serve. Local Police and Crime Panels (PCPs) have the appropriate powers, agreed by Parliament, to effectively scrutinise the actions and decisions of PCCs and ultimately, the public will hold PCCs to account at the ballot box.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-06T17:27:47.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782165/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782165/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Police and Crime Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to improve the performance monitoring of Police and Crime Commissioners.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782166","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The recently announced package of reforms for the National Referral Mechanism (NRM) incorporated a number of measures that will improve the NRM process for children. These measures were informed by an evaluation of an 18 month pilot testing changes to the NRM process, including multi-agency decision-making, for both adult and child cases.</p><p>The creation of a single, expert unit within the Home Office, to make decisions about whether somebody is a victim of modern slavery, will replace the current case management units in the National Crime Agency and UK Visas and Immigration, and will be separate from the immigration system. A priority for the new unit will be to ensure that it has the right balance of diverse expertise to be able to make effective decisions.</p><p>The creation of an independent multi-agency panel to review all negative NRM decisions will not only increase confidence in the decision making process but will also significantly add to the scrutiny each case currently receives.</p><p>In addition, we will roll out Independent Child Trafficking Advocates (ICTAs) nationally, and continue testing innovative ways of supporting trafficked children through the £2.2m funding we granted as part of the Child Trafficking Protection Fund. We will also explore how to make the NRM decision-making process more ‘child-friendly’, including looking at how we communicate NRM decisions to children and considering how local authorities can contribute to the decision-making process in a more consistent and structured way.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-07T15:50:56.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782166/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782166/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Human Trafficking: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of how the changes to the National Referral Mechanism announced on 17 October 2017 will affect children; and whether she has made an assessment of the potential merits of implementing multi-agency decision-making in cases involving potential child victims of trafficking.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","110815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782167","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Official statistics, published by the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) show that two people have died as a result of committing suicide whilst being held in police custody since 2010/11; one in 2014/15 and the other 2016/17.</p><p>IPCC’s annual statistics on deaths during or following police contact can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.ipcc.gov.uk/page/deaths-during-or-following-police-contact" target="_blank">https://www.ipcc.gov.uk/page/deaths-during-or-following-police-contact</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-06T17:16:35.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782167/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782167/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Police Custody: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many deaths in police custody were classified as suicide for each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","110796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782168","Home Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Home Office publishes quarterly figures on the number of asylum seekers housed in dispersed accommodation, including under Section 95, by local authority in the Immigration Statistics release, in table as_16q and 17q in volume 4 of the Asylum data tables. These are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/how-many-people-do-we-grant-asylum-or-protection-to" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/how-many-people-do-we-grant-asylum-or-protection-to</a></p><p>Figures on the number of those accommodated under Section 95 by constituency could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-08T14:21:14.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782168/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782168/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Asylum: Glasgow South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers are resident in Glasgow South West constituency.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","110788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782169","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Minister for State for Crime, Safeguarding and Vulnerability announced on 26 October that this Government remains committed to rolling out Independent Child Trafficking Advocates (ICTAs) nationally.</p><p>That is why we have implemented ICTAs in three Early Adopter Sites (Greater Manchester, Hampshire and the Isle of Wight and nationally in Wales) in order to make sure we implement the right model which best supports the specific and diverse needs of these incredibly vulnerable children.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-06T17:29:49.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782169/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782169/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Human Trafficking: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to roll out the Independent Child Trafficking Advocate scheme nationally.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","110804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782170","Home Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Home Office and our asylum accommodation provider in Scotland are in regular contact with representatives from the Scottish Government and Glasgow City Council on accommodation standards through forums such as the Scottish Asylum Dispersal Strategy Group, Asylum Stakeholders Forum and the Scottish Asylum Procurement Group.</p><p>In Glasgow, all new property procurement proposals are individually considered by the Local Authority.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-08T14:24:18.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782170/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782170/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Asylum: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with (a) the Scottish Government and (b) Glasgow City Council to ensure that contractors of asylum seeker services comply with the provisions of housing legislation in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","110789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782171","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government estimates that 9,000-11,000 businesses are required to publish statements. We do not have a definitive list of those businesses or a specific estimate of non-compliance. There are two independent websites which collate published statements at <a href="https://tiscreport.org" target="_blank">https://tiscreport.org</a> and <a href="http://www.modernslaveryregistry.org" target="_blank">www.modernslaveryregistry.org</a></p><p>The Government is taking action to improve compliance. We recently wrote to over 10,000 businesses that may be required to publish statements reminding them of their obligations and pointing them towards relevant guidance. We have also strengthened the wording in our guidance to set out our expectations for these statements more clearly.</p><p>In October the Government also launched a new ‘Business Against Slavery Forum’. This aims to establish a new partnership between Government and business to accelerate progress in tackling modern slavery. It will focus on sharing best practice and building new initiatives to tackle modern slavery, including improving business engagement with the Modern Slavery Act 2015.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-06T17:37:31.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782171/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782171/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of organisations which have failed to publish a statement under section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 within the timeframes set out in Government guidelines; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alex Norris","Nottingham North","Alex Norris","110772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782172","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Home Office holds information on those IT and digital assets provided by the Home Office to Arms Lengths Bodies and are supported by the Home Office Data Digital and Technology function. Some services supporting Arms Lengths Bodies are provided under arrangements managed directly by the bodies themselves and they would hold the relevant asset information.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-06T17:37:43.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782172/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782172/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","Home Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782173","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-08","<p>DFID’s arm’s-length bodies consist of ICAI and the Commonwealth Scholarships Commission. The Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets provided to them by DFID. The Department does not hold any information relating to other IT or digital assets in use by these bodies.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-08T09:30:37.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782173/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782173/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-01","Department for International Development: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782174","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-07","<p>According to the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (UN OCHA), lifesaving services are being run on generators in Gaza as a result of electricity shortages, with many vital health, water and sanitation facilities being provided with emergency UN fuel to continue operating. The UK is supporting approximately 1 million Gazans by addressing critical water, sanitation and hygiene needs through the United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF), and is a long-term supporter of the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestinian Refugees (UNRWA), which provides basic services to 1.3 million people in Gaza, including basic health care. The UK will continue to urge all the parties to prioritise progress towards reaching a durable solution for Gaza and to take the necessary practical steps to improve condition, including restoring the availability of electricity as a matter of urgency.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-07T12:54:53.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782174/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782174/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-01","Gaza: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect of the electricity crisis in Gaza on healthcare services.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","110755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782175","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-06","<p>The UK Government is aware of recent reports of an increase in the number of cases of malaria in Darfur. Malaria remains a serious concern in Sudan. We will continue to contribute to the treatment of malaria (and other diseases) in Sudan through the Global Fund, a multilateral organisation which has invested nearly $33 billion in the treatment of diseases in Sudan since 2002, including malaria. In its 2017 report, the Global Fund reported that, between 2002 and 2015, the number of new malaria cases had declined by 60%, and mortality rates had declined by 62%.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-06T16:09:59.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782175/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782175/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-01","Darfur: Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate her Department has made of the extent of recent increases in malaria cases in Darfur, Sudan; and what the implications of that increase are for her Department's policies in that region.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","110769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782177","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-06","<p>The World Health Organisation has a strong presence in the Greater Mekong Sub Region (including Vietnam): it continuously works with national governments to assess multidrug resistance and support policy responses. DFID supports the WHO in this essential work. Despite the real concern about drug resistance in Vietnam and the Sub Region, there has been a major decline in the rate of malaria cases and deaths. In Vietnam, between 2013 and 2015, the reported cases declined from 17,128 to 9,331 cases and reported deaths from 6 to 3.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-06T15:57:25.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782177/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782177/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-01","Vietnam: Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the increasing number of drug-resistant malaria cases in Vietnam and of the growing prevalence of anti-malarial drug resistance in the Greater Mekong Region.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","110910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782178","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Sentencing Guideline for environmental offences was reviewed and strengthened in 2014. The maximum penalty on indictment for fly-tipping is imprisonment of up to five years or a potentially unlimited fine. The Government will continue to provide information to the Sentencing Council as they monitor the impact of the guidance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to tackling fly-tipping at all levels. We have recently given local authorities the power to issue fixed penalty notices for small scale fly-tipping and enhanced the local authorities’ and the Environment Agency’s ability to search and seize vehicles of suspected fly-tippers.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-06T16:35:57.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782178/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782178/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Fly-tipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will take steps to increase the level of sentencing for fly-tipping.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","110909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782179","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Department has not undertaken such an assessment.</p><p>Unrepresented parties have always been a feature of the civil and family justice system. Since 2015, the Government has invested £5 million of funding to support litigants in person through a range of measures designed to provide additional information, support and guidance.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-06T17:39:33.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782179/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782179/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-01","Legal Representation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department has undertaken an assessment of the number of sitting hours courts have lost as a result of people deciding to represent themselves in court.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","110802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782180","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>Determining sentences for children and young people in individual cases is a matter for the relevant sentencing court. The distinct sentencing framework for the youth justice system provides a range of robust options for courts, including custody in the most serious cases. This includes long-term or extended sentence of detention or detention for life, if relevant criteria are met; and detention at Her Majesty’s pleasure, for murder convictions.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-11-06T13:11:32.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782180/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782180/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-01","Sentencing: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans the Government has to review sentence levels for young people under the age of 18 who commit a crime so serious that they are deemed unsafe to their local community.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","110773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782181","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-08","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service recognises the need for refurbishment of Sunderland Magistrates’ Court. We are committed to maintaining and improving the building. Work is already planned to address safety, security and accessibility concerns. A recent condition survey highlighted a number of issues which will be addressed in order of priority as soon as is reasonably practical and as resources allow.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-08T17:38:55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782181/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782181/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-01","Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will visit the court building in Sunderland to assess the need for refurbishment.","true","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","110760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782182","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-06T17:34:26.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782182/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782182/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-01","Antisemitism: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted of offences as a result of anti-Semitic views in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","110765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782183","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>Statistics on the number of escapes from prison custody are published in the supplementary tables of the HMPPS Annual Digest, which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>Statistics are not collected in a way that distinguishes between convicted and unconvicted prisoners. The rate of escapes per 1,000 prisoners is less than 1 per 1,000 for each of the last five years.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-06T13:04:03.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782183/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782183/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-01","Prisoner Escapes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average rate has been for convicted prisoners escaping from custody per 1,000 prisoners in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","110764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782184","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) has 32 agencies and public bodies, most of which have sole control of their own digital and IT assets. For that reason, the MoJ does not currently hold a central list of IT and digital assets of its arm’s-length bodies.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-11-09T15:20:29.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782184/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782184/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-01","Ministry of Justice: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782185","Leader of the House","false","2017-11-06","<p>The implementation of laws and policies that are devolved to Scotland are the responsibility of the Scottish Government. They are, therefore, accountable for all devolved decision making, and these matters should be raised in the Scottish Parliament with the Scottish Government.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-11-06T11:32:21.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782185/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782185/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-11-01","Scottish Government: Parliamentary Scrutiny","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to her Oral Statement on 26 October 2017, Official Report, column 461, what she meant by her statement that she would encourage her hon. Friends to hold the Scottish Government to account.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","110771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782186","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>This information is not held centrally as the management of IT and digital assets is an operational matter for individual arms-length bodies which operate independently from central government.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-11-09T17:40:37.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782186/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782186/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-11-01","Northern Ireland Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782187","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>There are differing views among the political parties in Northern Ireland on reforming the Petition of Concern mechanism. The Government would like to see the issue resolved on the basis of consensus between the parties.</p><p> </p><p>The parties agreed as part of the Stormont House Agreement that changes will be made to the operation of the Petition of Concern mechanism through a protocol agreed between the parties.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains committed to the full implementation of the Stormont House Agreement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><br> <br></p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-11-06T12:12:34.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782187/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782187/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-11-01","Northern Ireland Assembly: Petition of Concern","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of bringing forward legislative proposals to reform the Northern Ireland Assembly's petition of concern; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782188","Scotland Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Scotland Office is responsible for one arms-length-body, the Boundary Commission for Scotland. The Boundary Commission for Scotland makes its own arrangements for information technology and its current system is provided by the Scottish Government. As such my department does not hold a central list of the Commission’s IT and digital assets.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-11-08T12:55:04.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782188/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782188/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-11-01","Scotland Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782189","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department for Transport’s arm’s-length bodies are:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li>Network Rail</li><li>British Transport Police</li><li>Highways England</li><li>HS2 Ltd</li></ul><p> </p><p>We can confirm that we do not hold a central list of their IT and digital assets.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-08T10:13:59.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782189/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782189/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Department for Transport: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782190","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) has been working closely with the railway industry to reduce emissions from diesel trains, including freight services. All new diesel trains are fitted with engines that meet stringent emission limits set by the EU Non-road Mobile Machinery (NRMM) directive. As older rolling stock comes to the end of its working life, new engines are now being introduced that are fully compliant with these standards.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-08T10:17:33.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782190/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782190/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Trains: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to reduce pollution from diesel locomotives used for freight services.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782191","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Secretary of State would expect Greater Manchester authorities to take the lead in developing local transport around Leigh, including any proposals for links to future HS2 stations. The government has committed £300m to future-proof HS2 to support Transport for the North’s ambition for Northern Powerhouse Rail (NPR) between the North’s largest cities.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-07T16:34:57.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782191/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782191/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Railways: Leigh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Transport for the North on rail and High Speed 2 connectivity in Leigh.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782192","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The key issue for a new direct train service between Oxford and Bristol is the lack of spare track capacity. Enhancements to the route to enable additional train services would need to be considered alongside other rail infrastructure upgrades in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>On 12 October 2017 the Transport Secretary set out the final Statement of Funds Available for the railway in England and Wales for Control Period 6, which covers the years 2019 to 2024.</p><p> </p><p>The Department needs to ensure investment best addresses the needs of passengers and freight, and that funding commitments appropriately reflect the stage of development of those enhancements. This is why there will be a new process for enhancements, building on the principles set out in the ‘Memorandum of Understanding between Department for Transport and Network Rail on rail enhancements’ last year. We’ll set out more information on this new process shortly.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-08T10:20:29.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782192/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782192/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Bristol-Oxford Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential benefits of reintroducing passenger services between Oxford and Bristol; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782193","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-06","<p>When evaluating the scheme, transport related benefits including travel time, operating costs and reliability were taken into account. The Value for Money assessment for the scheme was less than 1, meaning for every £1 invested, there would have been a loss to the UK economy in terms of return.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-06T14:28:51.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782193/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782193/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","M62: M606","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential economic effect of the decision to review improvements to the M62/M606 Chain Bar road junction on local businesses and communities.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","110775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782194","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department is beginning its work on the specification and procurement of the next Cross Country franchise which is due to begin in 2019. Improving capacity and value for money will be high on the list of priorities for the next franchisee.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-08T09:54:59.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782194/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782194/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Railways: Oxford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase (a) capacity and (b) value for money for passengers on Cross Country services to and from Oxford.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782195","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government believes it is for local authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) to determine the best way to meet local transport needs. It would be for Transport for Greater Manchester to develop such plans and look for funding.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-07T16:39:36.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782195/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782195/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Railways: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential ways to reduce journey times between Leigh railway station and Wigan North Western railway station.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782196","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-06","<p>When renewing their driving entitlement at the age of 70, licence holders must declare that they can continue to meet the relevant medical standards, including as regards their eyesight. The law requires all driving licence holders, regardless of age, to notify the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) of any medical condition that could affect their fitness to drive. Failure to do so is an offence.</p><p> </p><p>If a driver of any age notifies the DVLA of a medical condition, an investigation will be carried out. This can involve requesting additional information from the applicant’s doctors, or they may be asked to attend a medical examination with a DVLA-appointed doctor.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-06T14:17:30.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782196/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782196/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Driving: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what medical evidence motorists are required to provide to the DVLA regarding fitness on reaching the age of 70; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","110911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782197","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Government’s priorities for improving road safety are set out in the British Road Safety Statement. We intend to publish a progress report towards the end of this year. Funding is being made available through the £175million Safer Roads Fund to improve the safety of the most dangerous local A-roads in England. The THINK! Country roads campaign targets improving safety on rural roads. Casualties on rural roads in 2016 were 6% lower than in 2012.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-08T10:02:23.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782197/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782197/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Roads: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made in increasing safety on rural roads in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","110837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782198","Wales Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Leaving the EU gives us the unique opportunity to shape our own ambitious trade and investment opportunities and it is important that future trade policy, including decisions on future tariff levels, delivers for the whole of the UK, including Wales. I hold regular discussions with the Secretary of State for International Trade, and I, as a member of the Trade Committee, and my officials, are working closely with the Department for International Trade on their broader work and analysis. We will continue to ensure that full consideration is given to any potential economic impact on Wales, including in relation to specific sectors, as the trade work develops.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-11-06T11:55:17.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782198/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782198/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-11-01","Trade Barriers: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, if his Department will make an assessment of the effects of abolishing external tariffs on the production of (a) steel, (b) lamb, and (c) agricultural produce in Wales.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","110958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782199","Wales Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Wales Office does not have any arm's-length bodies.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-11-06T11:53:24.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782199/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782199/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-11-01","Wales Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782200","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government is planning to publish its response to the Women and Equalities Committee report on <em>Building for Equality: Disability and the Built Environment</em>, shortly.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-09T13:48:01.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782200/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782200/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-01","Building Regulations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when the Government plans to respond to the ninth report of the Women and Equalities Committee's report, Building for Equality: Disability and the Built Environment of Session 2016-17, HC 631, published on 25 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782201","Women and Equalities","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Equalities and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) is allocated an overall annual budget, which is £19.3m in the current financial year. Funding for EHRC’s promotional activities is included within that budget. Decisions on allocation of resources within its overall budget are matters for the EHRC as an independent public body subject to Cabinet Office spending controls which apply to non Departmental public bodies.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-11-09T16:40:23.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782201/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782201/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-11-01","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what plans she has to provide funding for the advertising of services provided by the Equalities and Human Rights Commission; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","110790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782202","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>I can confirm that the amendments have been made to the aforementioned Regulations and were laid before Parliament on 23 October.</p><p> </p><p>They are due to come into force on the 15<sup>th</sup> November 2017 and will be known as “The Social Security (Information-sharing in relation to Welfare Services etc.) (Amendment) Regulations 2017”.</p><p> </p><p>These amendments will allow the Department for Work and Pensions to provide information on people aged between 18 and 25 who are in receipt of Jobseeker’s Allowance, Employment and Support Allowance or Universal Credit to Careers Wales (a wholly owned subsidiary of the Welsh Government) and to allow Careers Wales to hold such information to allow them to provide advice, assistance and support to such persons.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-07T17:02:36.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782202/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782202/answer","110834 - EM (info regs)2017.pdf","EM (info regs) 2017","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782202/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Social Security Benefits: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to amend the Social Security (Information-sharing in relation to Welfare Service etc) Regulations 2012 to enable data-sharing on employment and training between his Department and the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","110834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782203","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>There are no claim forms as applications for Universal Credit Full Service are either made online or via telephone. The application process is personalised and tailored to the claimant’s circumstances and answers so not all claimants are asked the same questions.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-06T17:43:39.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782203/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782203/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he will place a copy of the universal credit application form in the Library.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","110855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782204","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>We are currently considering the Tribunal’s ruling.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-06T15:00:49.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782204/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782204/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to amend his Department's guidance on the use of transcripts in personal independence payment assessments following the result of the tribunal hearing for Neville Cartwright.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","110828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782205","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>I have been asked to respond on behalf of the Secretary of State.</p><p> </p><p>Invitations to Ministers are considered when they are received. However it should be noted that the policy on up-rating state pensions abroad is quite clear and has remained consistent for around 70 years; the UK State Pension is payable world wide but is only uprated abroad where there is a legal requirement to do so. Ministers and officials from this Department have discussed UK state pensions with leaders and representatives of the British Overseas Territories in recent years, including attendance at Joint Ministerial Councils.</p><p> </p><p>Officials talk on a regular basis but the UK government has not proposed a change of policy on this issue for 70 years.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-06T14:18:57.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782205/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782205/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Pensioners: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will meet leaders of British Overseas Territories to discuss UK pensioners residing in those territories whose pensions have not been uprated.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","110861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782206","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government established the Pensions Regulator as an independent body to provide regulatory oversight of work based pension schemes. As such, the Department for Work and Pensions does not have access to the information that the Regulator holds in relation to individual pension schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Section 82 of the Pensions Act 2004 prevents the disclosure of such restricted information by the Regulator or by any person who receives the information directly or indirectly from the Regulator, except in certain, prescribed, circumstances, none of which are judged to apply in this case.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-07T11:54:44.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782206/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782206/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Pensions Regulator: Universities Superannuation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will place in the Library all correspondence undertaken between the Pensions Regulator and (a) the Universities Superannuation Scheme and (b) Universities UK since the actuarial valuation in 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","110868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782207","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-08","<p>There is no data broken down by area or region. The latest statistics on Universal Credit Advances were published on 02 October 2017 which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-payment-advances-may-2016-to-june-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-payment-advances-may-2016-to-june-2017</a>. This shows that, in July 2017, 8,400 new claims to UC Full Service received either a New Claim or Benefit Transfer Advance. This represents 52% of new claims that are eligible for a UC payment.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-08T10:21:08.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782207/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782207/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Universal Credit: Leigh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people claiming universal credit in Leigh have requested an advance on their payments in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782208","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-06T11:31:41.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782208/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782208/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Personal Independence Payment: Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many former claimants of disability living allowance in Hull West and Hessle constituency who have been unsuccessful in their claim for personal independence payments have been waiting (a) over six weeks, (b) over three months and (c) over six months for their appeal to be heard; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","110844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782209","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The information requested is not available</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-06T17:48:07.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782209/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782209/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) shortest, (b) average and (c) longest time taken for new universal credit claimants to (i) register, (ii) open their online account, (iii) submit relevant information to his Department and (iv) make their declaration in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","110908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782210","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>The DWP has a database of the devices which are deployed to DWP staff and to all the other users (contractors, suppliers, relevant OGDs and Arm’s length bodies with access to DWP systems).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-07T16:57:11.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782210/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782210/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Department for Work and Pensions: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782211","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>DWP’s priority is to ensure homeless people get the appropriate support they need to move into work so they can succeed and rebuild their lives.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that homeless veterans may face particular challenges in getting into employment. Support provided by DWP in Great Britain complements that offered by the Career Transition Partnership and other organisations supporting veterans.</p><p> </p><p>The homeless and ex-HM Armed Forces personnel form two of the specified priority groups for the forthcoming Work and Health Programme. This allows for early voluntary entry to the programme at the most appropriate time in their claim for those who would benefit from specialist employment support to find work. In addition, DWP provides a range of support to help homeless people into work. This includes access to the Jobcentre Plus employment offer with individual tailoring. DWP’s National Employer and Partnership Team also work with national employer and partner organisations to help ex-HM Armed Forces Service leavers into employment.</p><p> </p><p>The Department also recognises as a priority that claimants who have recently become homeless will need time to try and resolve their accommodation issues, and so jobseeking requirements can temporarily be put on hold whilst homeless claimants find accommodation and claimants directed to concentrate on seeking additional support through various homeless organisations instead; and where sanctions are applied they can access hardship payments immediately. The removal of housing support for 18-21 year olds policy includes a wide-ranging set of exemptions which means homeless people will not be affected.</p><p> </p><p>Underpinning DWP’s support for veterans and serving personnel and their families is our network of Armed Forces Champions in each Jobcentre Plus district who support work coaches in understanding the range of support available to Service leavers and ensure they are actively signposted to appropriate organisations.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-06T15:23:44.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782211/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782211/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-01","Veterans: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department offers to homeless ex-service personnel to ensure that they receive adequate training for sustainable employment.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","110766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782212","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p>We are unable to provide statistics on how many consumers with SMETS1 meters have switched energy suppliers since the programme began.</p><p> </p><p>According to Ofgem’s report, ‘Consumer engagement in the energy market 2017’, 23% of consumers who say they have a smart meter have switched supplier in the past 12 months, compared to 17% of those who say they do not have a smart meter.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-09T14:12:33.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782212/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782212/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many domestic energy customers with SMETS1 smart meters have switched energy suppliers since the roll-out programme began.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","110762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782213","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>We are unable to provide statistics on smart meter installations broken down by region and nation.</p><p> </p><p>Collectively across both large and small suppliers, around 7.36 million smart meters (SMETS1) have been installed in domestic properties in Great Britain to the end of June 2017.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that large supplier statistics are collected at the end of each calendar quarter and small supplier statistics are collected annually, at the end of the calendar year. Therefore installations carried out by small suppliers since 31 December 2016 are not reflected in the above figure. The rollout is also across Great Britain only.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-09T14:14:30.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782213/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782213/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many SMETS1 smart meters have been fitted in domestic premises in each nation and region of the UK since the start of the smart meter roll-out.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","110761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782214","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p>There have been regular discussions with the Manufacturing Technology Association (MTA) on a range of issues of importance to the sector, including the implications of EU exit for MTA member companies. As we continue to engage with MTA and industry more widely, we remain committed to making the UK the best place in Europe to own and grow a business. That includes supporting those businesses that trade with the EU and wider international markets, as well as continuing to encourage record foreign direct investment that supports business and communities up and down the country.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-11-09T14:10:23.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782214/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782214/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Manufacturing Technologies Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Manufacturing Technologies Association on plans to relocate jobs to Europe after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782215","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Food and drink is the UK’s largest manufacturing sector employing 400,000 people. The UK food and drink supply chain (including farmers, manufacturers, wholesalers, retailers, catering, and restaurants) contributed £108 billion to the UK economy in 2014, and employed 1 in 8 workers. As a geographically diverse sector, the success of the industry is crucial to driving growth across the country, a key objective of Industrial Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Industrial Strategy, Government is supporting all sectors across the economy to grow, invest and reach their potential. Our new approach also challenges individual sectors to upgrade through “Sector Deals” - an open challenge to industry to come to us with proposals to transform their sector. We are prepared to work with any sector which can organise behind strong leadership to address shared challenges and opportunities.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-11-09T14:18:10.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782215/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782215/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Agriculture and Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the importance of the food and farming sector in the new industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782216","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government is working hard to support businesses and entrepreneurs across the UK to ensure they can access the finance and wider support to grow and have the right conditions for companies to invest long-term. The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy publicises these services in a range of ways, including online channels, information delivered by local partners; and regular engagements with businesses, entrepreneurs, representative bodies and others.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-06T16:15:48.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782216/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782216/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Small Businesses: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to publicise the services his Department provides to enable small business to grow their businesses throughout the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","110743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782217","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm’s-length bodies.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-09T09:05:57.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782217/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782217/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782218","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-08","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State and his Ministerial team regularly meet UK owned, and UK operations of foreign owned multi-national businesses. Engagement with businesses covers the whole aspect of BEIS responsibilities. This includes detailed discussions on developing our industrial strategy that will ensure the UK continues to be an attractive place for foreign owned businesses to invest; and improve the productivity and competitiveness of all businesses operating in the UK.</p><p>Details of meetings are made public; the latest publication was on 13 October 2017 covering the period between April and June 2017. It can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/beis-ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings-april-to-june-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/beis-ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings-april-to-june-2017</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-08T12:58:35.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782218/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782218/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Foreign Companies: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with foreign-owned businesses on maintaining the competitiveness of their UK operations after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782219","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department has engaged with over 500 businesses across the UK to understand the potential impacts of customs delays. We will continue to work closely with business.</p><p>This is a complex issue which could affect a wide range of sectors. We are working with the Department for Exiting the EU and the Treasury to reflect business concerns, minimise disruption and maximise certainty.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-08T12:57:00.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782219/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782219/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect on businesses close to major ports of customs delays after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782220","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department receives many letters from the general public regarding a wide range of issues. The Government continues to work closely with regulators and with the shale industry to ensure that any concerns the general public may be experiencing are appropriately addressed.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-09T14:16:17.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782220/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782220/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations he has received from the general public expressing concerns on fracking for shale gas.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","110839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782221","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-06","<p>Staffing levels of postal operators is a matter for the individual businesses concerned.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-06T14:22:47.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782221/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782221/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Postal Workers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department has taken to assist in the retention of postal workers.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782222","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>The table below provides provisional figures for the 2016/17 academic year on the number of apprenticeship starts for learners with and without a learning difficulty and disability.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17 Full Year (Provisional)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage Distribution</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Learning Difficulty/Disability</p></td><td><p>50,470</p></td><td><p>10.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>No Learning Difficulty/Disability</p></td><td><p>434,050</p></td><td><p>88.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not Known</p></td><td><p>6,820</p></td><td><p>1.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>491,300</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>100.0%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Note: </strong>Total figures are rounded to the nearest hundred.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeship data is collected via the Individualised Learner Record (ILR). The ILR does not hold information on statements of special educational need for apprenticeship learners, this is only collected for school pupils via the school census. Information on Learners with Learning Difficulties and/or Disabilities is self-declared by the learner and covers a wider range of both learning difficulties and disabilities. For further information on apprenticeship starts by demographic breakdowns, please refer to the demographic data tool via:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650223/201617_Oct_Apps_Demographic_Data_Tool_FINAL.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650223/201617_Oct_Apps_Demographic_Data_Tool_FINAL.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>The table attached provides provisional traineeship starts figures for the 2016/17 academic year along with the percentage changes in comparison to finalised figures from each of the three previous years. Comparisons to previous academic years should be made with caution as the provisional figures are subject to change. Final 2016/17 academic year figures will be published on 23 November 2017.</p><p><br>For further information on traineeship starts by academic year, please refer to the October SFR main tables via:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650552/SFR_53_2017_main_tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650552/SFR_53_2017_main_tables.ods</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","110826","2017-11-09T15:16:48.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782222/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782222/answer","110825, 110826 Attachment.docx.pdf","Provisional traineeship starts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782222/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Apprentices: Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of apprenticeship starts have been taken up by learners with learning difficulties and disabilities and special education needs and disability in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","110825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782223","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>The table below provides provisional figures for the 2016/17 academic year on the number of apprenticeship starts for learners with and without a learning difficulty and disability.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17 Full Year (Provisional)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage Distribution</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Learning Difficulty/Disability</p></td><td><p>50,470</p></td><td><p>10.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>No Learning Difficulty/Disability</p></td><td><p>434,050</p></td><td><p>88.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not Known</p></td><td><p>6,820</p></td><td><p>1.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>491,300</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>100.0%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Note: </strong>Total figures are rounded to the nearest hundred.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeship data is collected via the Individualised Learner Record (ILR). The ILR does not hold information on statements of special educational need for apprenticeship learners, this is only collected for school pupils via the school census. Information on Learners with Learning Difficulties and/or Disabilities is self-declared by the learner and covers a wider range of both learning difficulties and disabilities. For further information on apprenticeship starts by demographic breakdowns, please refer to the demographic data tool via:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650223/201617_Oct_Apps_Demographic_Data_Tool_FINAL.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650223/201617_Oct_Apps_Demographic_Data_Tool_FINAL.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>The table attached provides provisional traineeship starts figures for the 2016/17 academic year along with the percentage changes in comparison to finalised figures from each of the three previous years. Comparisons to previous academic years should be made with caution as the provisional figures are subject to change. Final 2016/17 academic year figures will be published on 23 November 2017.</p><p><br>For further information on traineeship starts by academic year, please refer to the October SFR main tables via:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650552/SFR_53_2017_main_tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650552/SFR_53_2017_main_tables.ods</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","110825","2017-11-09T15:16:48.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782223/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782223/answer","110825, 110826 Attachment.docx.pdf","Provisional traineeship starts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782223/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-01","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the percentage change was in the number of traineeship starts in 2016-17 from that number in each of the previous three years.","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","110826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782224","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-06","<p>We have analysed the responses and are in the process of further investigating some of the suggestions before publishing the Government response. In the meantime, I would like to assure the hon. Member that we are continuing to work with industry and enforcement partners to build a coordinated response to the growth of illicit streaming.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-06T14:24:42.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782224/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782224/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Television: Copyright","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish his Department's response to the Intellectual Property Office call for views on IPTV set-top boxes, which closed on 7 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","110857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782225","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-08","<p>Discussions have been held with a range of stakeholders, most recently roundtables with representatives of the drinks and coffee cup industries.</p><p> </p><p>Officials receive regular updates from the Advisory Committee on Packaging (ACP), who represent all parts of the packaging supply chain, on a wide range of issues relating to the Directive and the UK’s implementing Regulations. The ACP last met on 24 October.</p><p> </p><p>Amendments to the Packaging Directive form part of the proposals for a Circular Economy Package (CEP). This package is currently under negotiation, involving regular and ongoing discussions with the Commission.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-08T17:52:20.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782225/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782225/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Packaging: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the packaging industry about the Packaging and Packaging Waste Directive (94/62/EC); and whether he has made representations to the European Commission on that directive.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","110833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782226","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-03","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer I gave to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-10-27/110155/" target="_blank">110155</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-03T11:31:43.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782226/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782226/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Nuclear Fusion: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what budget has been allocated to research on nuclear fusion until 29 March 2019.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","110808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782227","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union regularly meets with counterparts in the EU to discuss a range of matters relating to the UK's Exit from the EU.<br><br></p><p>The Government set out its position in relation to future customs arrangements with the EU in a Future Relationship Paper in August.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-09T17:11:10.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782227/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782227/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","EU Internal Trade: Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in the EU on customs arrangements for movement of goods within Europe after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782228","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-09","<p>In our negotiations with the EU, the UK will seek to secure a new, deep and special partnership. We propose the greatest possible tariff- and barrier-free trade with our European neighbours based on our rules and regulations being the same at the start, and on maintaining our commitment to free trade and high standards.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>But there will be areas that affect our economic relations where we and our European friends may have different goals; or where we share the same goals but want to achieve them through different means. This is where we recognise that the single market is built on a balance of rights and obligations, and so our task is to find a new framework that allows for a close economic partnership but holds those rights and obligations in a new and different balance.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-09T17:07:41.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782228/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782228/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the importance of regulatory alignment to the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782229","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-09","<p>Officials from the Department for International trade have met the Manufacturing Technologies Association to discuss a wide range of issues important to the manufacturing sector. This department regularly meets with stakeholders from all sectors to help shape a UK trade policy that works for all.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-11-09T17:01:38.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782229/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782229/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-01","Manufacturing Technologies Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he has had with the Manufacturing Technologies Association on (a) frictionless trade and (b) the ability to influence international standards after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782230","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department of International Trade’s (DIT) officials and I maintain close contact with the food and drink industry; and agriculture.</p><p> </p><p>The ministerial team have had a variety of very productive meetings with a range of industry representatives.</p><p> </p><p>In carrying out our engagement with the industry we cooperate closely with Defra and other government departments.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-09T12:13:54.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782230/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782230/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-01","Agriculture: Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with representatives of the food and farming sectors on the development of new trade deals with other countries.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782231","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Department for international Trade currently has no arms-length bodies, and therefore keeps no such lists.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-07T16:41:10.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782231/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782231/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-01","Department for International Trade: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782232","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Department engages regularly with stakeholders, including the British Chamber of Commerce, and welcomes their views on future trade deals.</p><p>The Government is seeking a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement with the EU and is pursuing the greatest possible tariff and barrier-free trade with our European neighbours. The Government is also committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships and will seek to transition all existing EU trade agreements and other EU preferential arrangements. The Government will continue to engage with stakeholders throughout the process, including the British Chambers of Commerce.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-07T15:55:58.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782232/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782232/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782232/answer/previousversion/20583","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-01","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of advice by the British Chamber of Commerce to prioritise a trade deal with (a) the EU and (b) other countries close to agreeing trade deals with the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782233","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-07","<p>As we made clear in both in our position paper and the Prime Minister’s speech in Florence, we must aim to avoid any physical infrastructure on the land border between Northern Ireland and Ireland and we welcome the Commission’s commitment to this in their Guiding principles paper.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The UK was also clear in the White Paper that we want to continue to see the everyday movements across the land border, and we recognise the importance of these movements to the economy in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-07T10:06:22.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782233/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782233/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the number of (a) official and (b) unofficial crossing points between the Irish Republic and Northern Ireland on the viability of any hard border between the UK and the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","110768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782234","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is working with departments across government to ensure that people and businesses have stability and certainty in the period leading up to our departure in March 2019, and that we use the opportunities that our EU exit presents to determine our own priorities. The government has guaranteed funding for all European Structural and Investment Fund projects signed before we leave the EU – provided they are value for money and in line with domestic priorities.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-07T16:12:40.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782234/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782234/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the re-payment of European Structural Investment Funds when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","110758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782235","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government is undertaking analysis of different scenarios, but will not publish any information that could undermine our negotiation position.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We will need to build a bridge from our exit to our future partnership, to allow business and people time to adjust, and to allow new systems to be put in place. It makes sense for there to be only one set of changes.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>That is why we are proposing a strictly time-limited implementation period, based on the existing structure of EU rules and regulations, during which the UK and the EU would continue to have access to one another’s markets on current terms, and the UK would take part in existing security measures.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The length of the period should be determined by how long it will take to prepare and implement the new processes and new systems – as the Prime Minister has said, this is likely to be for a period of around two years and it should be agreed as early as possible, so as to provide certainty.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-09T12:05:59.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782235/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782235/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","Business: Transitional Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the benefit to businesses and the economy of a transition period of three years or longer as called for by the British Chambers of Commerce.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782236","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union does not have any arm’s-length bodies.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-09T17:08:56.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782236/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782236/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","Department for Exiting the European Union: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department holds a central list of the IT and digital assets of its arm's-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782237","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p>We are working hard to support businesses and entrepreneurs across the UK to ensure they can access the wider support to grow and have the right conditions for companies to invest long-term. That’s why we are proposing a bold and ambitious free trade agreement as part of a new, deep and special partnership with the European Union.</p><p>In order to allow business time to adjust, we are also proposing a strictly time-limited implementation period where we continue to have access to one another’s markets on current terms.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-09T16:43:55.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782237/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782237/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-01","Government Assistance: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to support small businesses after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782238","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union participates in a childcare voucher scheme and has an active parenting and carers network to support staff. As a new department DExEU is in the process of forming its HR systems and processes, and we are also undertaking further work to provide support for childcare during school holidays.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-06T16:19:07.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782238/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782238/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782238/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","Department for Exiting the European Union: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what childcare facilities his Department makes available for staff; how much his Department spent (a) overall and (b) per child on those childcare facilities in the last year; and how many staff members use those childcare facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","110799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782239","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is working closely with other departments, including the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, to deliver the right outcome for UK businesses, including small businesses, as we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers from across Government have carried out extensive stakeholder engagement on EU Exit - with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy and all regions of the UK. In August 2016 the Prime Minister held a small business summit at Downing Street to hear the views and interests of small businesses. Representatives from trade associations including the Federation of Small Businesses (FSB) and the British Chambers of Commerce (BCC) were in attendance.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-10T12:34:32.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782239/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782239/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-01","Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions his Department has had with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the financial protections offered to small businesses after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","110835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782240","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government will bring forward an Order to bring the National Police Chiefs’ Council (NPCC) under the auspices of the Freedom of Information Act 2006 as soon as Parliamentary time allows. Before such an Order can be made, we will consult with the NPCC, as is required by legislation.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-06T17:18:27.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782240/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782240/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-01","National Police Chiefs' Council: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she expects an order to be brought forward bringing the National Police Chiefs Council under the auspices of the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782241","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>Current and historic duty rates for wine can be found in HM Revenue and Custom's published Alcohol Bulletin on the UK Trade Info website. This can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx</a></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-11-06T15:40:02.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782241/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782241/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Wines: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what has been the increase in duty on a bottle of English (a) still and (b) sparkling wine in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782242","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The government keeps all taxes under review. Any changes to wine duty rates would need to take account of a wide range of factors, including the Exchequer impact, the impact on businesses, public health and the distributional impact of reform.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-11-06T15:38:48.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782242/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782242/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Wines: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of regularising the rate of duty between still and sparkling wine.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782243","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>This information is not available as the government does not break down the amount of duty collected from spirits by Gin.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the amount of duty collected through alcohol taxation is routinely published online by HM Revenue &amp; Customs in the ‘Tax &amp; Duty Bulletins’ section of the UK Trade Info website. This can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-11-06T15:37:00.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782243/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782243/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Gin: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much tax revenue was generated from UK-produced Gin in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782244","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Scotland Act 2012 provided the Scottish Parliament with powers to replace UK Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT). Land and Buildings Transaction Tax replaced UK SDLT in Scotland from 1 April 2015. From April 2018, Land Transaction Tax will replace UK SDLT in Wales. The Government holds all taxes under review.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-11-07T16:41:47.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782244/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782244/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Stamp Duty Land Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing  regional rates of stamp duty.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782245","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has published a detailed summary of the main findings from the skilled person’s report. The FCA announced it is investigating the matters arising from the report and focussing on whether there is any basis for it to take further action. It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment further whilst this process is ongoing.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","110983 ; 110984 ; 110985 ; 110986","2017-11-06T13:56:16.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782245/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782245/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Global Restructuring Group","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the specialist advisers' report to the Treasury Committee of 31 October 2017, what assessment he has made of whether the Skilled Person's report commissioned by the Financial Conduct Authority contains a fair and balanced account of the findings of the Global Restructuring Group report.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782246","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has published a detailed summary of the main findings from the skilled person’s report. The FCA announced it is investigating the matters arising from the report and focussing on whether there is any basis for it to take further action. It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment further whilst this process is ongoing.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","110982 ; 110984 ; 110985 ; 110986","2017-11-06T13:56:17.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782246/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782246/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Global Restructuring Group","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the specialist advisers' report to the Treasury Committee of 31 October 2017, what assessment he has made of whether it would be fair or unfair to (a) people within and (b) SME customers of the Royal Bank of Scotland to publish relevant findings on management knowledge of the failings of the Global Restructuring Group report, commissioned by the Financial Conduct Authority.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782247","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has published a detailed summary of the main findings from the skilled person’s report. The FCA announced it is investigating the matters arising from the report and focussing on whether there is any basis for it to take further action. It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment further whilst this process is ongoing.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","110982 ; 110983 ; 110985 ; 110986","2017-11-06T13:56:17.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782247/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782247/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Global Restructuring Group","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will request that the Financial Conduct Authority publishes its Section 166 report into the Global Restructuring Group; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782248","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has published a detailed summary of the main findings from the skilled person’s report. The FCA announced it is investigating the matters arising from the report and focussing on whether there is any basis for it to take further action. It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment further whilst this process is ongoing.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","110982 ; 110983 ; 110984 ; 110986","2017-11-06T13:56:17.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782248/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782248/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the letter of 30 October 2017 from Ross McEwan, Chief Executive, Royal Bank of Scotland, to the Chair of the Treasury Committee on 31 October 2017, what assessment he has made of the validity of the areas of difference referred to by Mr McEwan in that letter.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782249","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has published a detailed summary of the main findings from the skilled person’s report. The FCA announced it is investigating the matters arising from the report and focussing on whether there is any basis for it to take further action. It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment further whilst this process is ongoing.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","110982 ; 110983 ; 110984 ; 110985","2017-11-06T13:56:16.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782249/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782249/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-01","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the letter of 30 October 2017 from Ross McEwan, Chief Executive, Royal Bank of Scotland, to the Chair of the Treasury Committee published by that Committee on 31 October 2017, what assessment he has made of the validity of the allegations made by the Skilled Person's report commissioned by the Financial Conduct Authority on (a) widespread inappropriate treatment of SME customers of the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), (b) systematic failure by RBS towards its SME customers, (c) material financial distress caused by RBS towards its SME customers and (d) implications of the turnaround findings referred to by Mr McEwan in that letter.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","110986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782250","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government recognises in the revised draft Airports National Policy Statement (NPS) the role of the Lakeside Energy from Waste plant in local waste management plans. The draft Airports NPS requires any future applicant for development consent to have assessed the effects of removing the plant upon capacity for treatment of waste and to make reasonable endeavours to ensure that sufficient provision is made to address the reduction in waste treatment capacity caused by the loss of the plant.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-06T15:12:37.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782250/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782250/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-01","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department will publish its assessment of the necessary changes to local waste management plans which will result from removing the Lakeside Energy from Waste plant in Slough as part of the proposed Heathrow Northwest Runway scheme.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","110899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782251","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department has considered the recommendations made by Eric Ollerenshaw in his review of local council tax support schemes. The Government response to the review’s findings will be published shortly.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-08T14:35:56.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782251/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782251/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-01","Council Tax Reduction Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Independent Review of local council tax support schemes by Eric Ollerenshaw, published in October 2016, if he will implement the recommendation in that review to commission academic research on the effect of local council tax support schemes within the wider context of other welfare and socio-economic changes.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","110922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782252","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>The English Housing Survey collects information about the number and proportion of households who are owner occupiers. Data for the last 10 years are available in Annex Table 1.1, published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595786/2015-16_Section_1_Households_Annex_Tables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595786/2015-16_Section_1_Households_Annex_Tables.xlsx</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-06T17:45:01.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782252/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782252/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782252/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-01","Owner Occupation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people have been owner-occupiers in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available; and what proportion those figures represent of total households.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","110902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782253","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government is committed to tackling fly-tipping on a number of fronts. Local authorities and the Environment Agency have a full range of enforcement powers to tackle fly-tipping which have recently been strengthened. We have given local authorities the power to issue fixed penalty notices for small scale fly-tipping and enhanced their ability to search and seize vehicles of suspected fly-tippers. It is the responsibility of local authorities to use the powers available to them. The National Fly-tipping Prevention Group has published guidance which sets out clearly the powers available to local authorities and other partners when tackling fly-tipping.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-06T18:22:02.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782253/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782253/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-01","Fly Tipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of steps taken by local authorities to counter fly-tipping.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","110903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782254","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>Local council tax support schemes are administered by local authorities. Councils are required to consult their local residents when designing their schemes and to take their views into account.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-06T17:41:58.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782254/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782254/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782254/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-01","Council Tax Reduction Schemes: Job Seeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect on jobseeker's allowance claimants of local authority council tax reduction schemes which do not exempt such claimants.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","110898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782255","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>Protecting the vulnerable is one of this Government’s key commitments. Supported housing helps a wide range of vulnerable people and is vital to help underpin this obligation. On Tuesday 31 October, Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth and I issued respective written statements to both Houses, setting out the arrangements for the future funding of supported housing (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-10-31/HCWS209/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-10-31/HCWS209/</a>).</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-06T17:39:51.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782255/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782255/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-01","Supported Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on the funding of supported housing.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","110930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782256","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>The proposed standard methodology for local housing need, published on 14 September, sets out the minimum numbers of homes that are needed in each area. It is the starting point in the process, not the end. Local authorities can plan for more homes should they wish where they expect future higher levels of growth than reflected in household projection, for example because of a major infrastructure project, to pursue employment opportunities, or because they want to pursue bespoke Housing Deals. Employment growth issues will be reflected both in local affordability issues and in changes to household projections over time.</p><p>To support that, the Government is investing £505 million in the North East and Tees Valley Local Enterprise Partnerships through their Growth Deals to help deliver their Strategic Economic Plans, which will create a reported 10,000 jobs.</p><p>The consultation closes on 9 November and I would encourage all interested parties to submit their comments.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","110946 ; 110947","2017-11-06T17:44:18.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782256/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782256/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782256/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-01","Housing: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of the new approach for determining local housing need in his Department's consultation, published on 14 September 2017, on housing stock in the North East.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","110945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782257","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>The proposed standard methodology for local housing need, published on 14 September, sets out the minimum numbers of homes that are needed in each area. It is the starting point in the process, not the end. Local authorities can plan for more homes should they wish where they expect future higher levels of growth than reflected in household projection, for example because of a major infrastructure project, to pursue employment opportunities, or because they want to pursue bespoke Housing Deals. Employment growth issues will be reflected both in local affordability issues and in changes to household projections over time.</p><p>To support that, the Government is investing £505 million in the North East and Tees Valley Local Enterprise Partnerships through their Growth Deals to help deliver their Strategic Economic Plans, which will create a reported 10,000 jobs.</p><p>The consultation closes on 9 November and I would encourage all interested parties to submit their comments.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","110945 ; 110946","2017-11-06T17:44:18.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782257/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782257/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782257/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-01","Housing: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that its approach to determining local housing need will contribute to reducing the difference between the North and the South of England in investment in and development of housing.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","110947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782258","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-06","<p>Data on ticket sales is a matter for Camelot, the National Lottery operator. Camelot releases detailed national sales information which can be found online at: http://www.camelotgroup.co.uk/about-us/reporting. Camelot does not release more granular sales data due to its commercially sensitive nature.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-11-06T16:53:15.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782258/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782258/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-01","Camelot Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department has seen or has access to regional sales data from Camelot.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","110944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782259","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government are responsibly preparing for a range of outcomes to ensure we have a smooth exit from the EU. The Government is engaging with businesses in every sector and region of the UK economy in order to understand the challenges and opportunities that may impact them in the coming months and years.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-11-06T12:02:28.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782259/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782259/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-01","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what involvement her Department has had in the preparation of a sectoral impact assessment into the effect of leaving the EU on (a) advertising and marketing, (b) architecture, (c) broadcasting, (d) crafts, (e) design, (f) gambling, (g) museums, galleries and libraries, (h) music, performing and visual arts, (i) publishing and (j) tourism.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","110940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782260","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department is planning a public consultation on treasure policy, which will primarily focus on proposed revisions to the Treasure Act 1996 Code of Practice.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-11-09T12:17:33.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782260/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782260/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-01","Treasure Act 1996","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans she has to review the effectiveness of the Treasure Act 1996.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782261","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-09","<p>Local authorities are responsible for allocating funding to youth services in line with local need. Section 251 data gathered by the Department for Education shows that between 2012/13 and 2015/16 total local authority spending on youth services has reduced by 36%.</p><p> </p><p>Local authority spending is only one part of the picture: many local authorities are creating new partnerships and models to respond to the changing funding landscape. Government has supported local authorities to adapt through the £700,000 Delivering Differently for Young People programme and is investing £80 million through the Youth Investment and #iwill Funds to increase opportunities for young people to develop skills and participate in their communities.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-11-09T12:24:44.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782261/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782261/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-01","Youth Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of trends in the level of spending on youth services excluding spending on the National Citizen Service.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782262","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government published a statement on the implementation of Positive for Youth in 2013. DCMS’ focus on youth policy builds on the legacy of Positive for Youth. This includes funding opportunities for young people to develop skills and participate in their communities and supporting the youth sector to develop its evidence base, sustainability and impact.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-11-09T12:23:03.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782262/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782262/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-01","Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she has taken to implement the Government's Positive for Youth policy on youth.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782263","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-09","<p>DCMS conducted a series of regional workshops in March and April 2017 with representatives from the youth sector, local authorities and young people to discuss current issues and opportunities for youth policy. The evidence gathered is being used by DCMS across its youth policy work.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-11-09T12:21:25.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782263/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782263/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-01","Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to publish the Government's updated youth policy.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","110972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782264","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-03","<p>No assessment has yet been made on the potential merits of increasing the number of UK Armed Forces personnel engaged in training and mentoring rangers.</p><p>Further to my answer of 31 October 2017 to Question 109460, on poaching, Liwonde National Park in Malawi was selected for a pilot project to test our methodology. Once the Pilot has concluded, we will conduct an evaluation of our approach and, where appropriate, make recommendations for subsequent training and mentoring activity.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-11-03T14:37:38.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782264/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782264/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-01","Poaching","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 31 October 2017 to Question 109460, on poaching, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of increasing the number of UK Armed Forces personnel engaged in training and mentoring rangers in areas where poaching takes place.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","110960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782265","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-08","<p>There are three Medical Deployability Standard (MDS) categories for the Armed Forces. Medically Fully Deployable (MFD) personnel are those medically fit for duty with no employment limitations. Medically Limited Deployable (MLD) personnel are medically fit for duty with minor employment limitations. MLD personnel may have a medical condition or functional limitation that prevents the meeting of all MFD requirements. Medically Not Deployable (MND) personnel are medically fit for duty with major employment limitations. MND personnel are not fit to deploy on Operations but may be deployable on UK based exercises.</p><p> </p><p>The table below provides the number (n) and percentage of UK Regular Armed Forces in each MDS category, by Service as at 1 April for each year since 2010. These figures include full time trained and serving personnel against requirement. This was the deployable population.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>All</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>MFD</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>MLD</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>MND</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Unknown MDS</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>n</strong></p></td><td><p>n</p></td><td><p><em>%</em></p></td><td><p>n</p></td><td><p><em>%</em></p></td><td><p>n</p></td><td><p><em>%</em></p></td><td><p>n</p></td><td><p><em>%</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2010</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All Services</p></td><td><p><strong>177,897 </strong></p></td><td><p>143,253</p></td><td><p><em>81%</em></p></td><td><p>18,101</p></td><td><p><em>10%</em></p></td><td><p>13,615</p></td><td><p><em>8%</em></p></td><td><p>2,928</p></td><td><p><em>2%</em></p></td></tr>